benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/catalog/versions - Retrieve a list of catalog versions

covered: Valid Request: Multiple scenarios (TC01, TC02, TC14) validate successful retrieval with and without accountId and compatibility with older clients.
Empty Response: TC03 and TC13 validate behavior when no catalog versions exist (empty JSON array, no stack traces).

Query Parameters: Extensive coverage — valid accountId (TC02), non-existent accountId (TC04), invalid format (TC05), empty (TC16), leading/trailing spaces (TC17), mixed case (TC18), unsupported extra parameters ignored (TC09), and SQL injection attempt (TC12).
Authorization: Authentication presence/absence and invalid/expired token are covered (TC06, TC07)
Response Format & Content-Type: Multiple scenarios assert application/json and that the body is a JSON array of ISO 8601 strings (TC01, TC02, TC20).
Error Handling: Client-side validation errors (400) and server-side issues (500) are represented (TC05, TC19), plus service-unavailable/timeouts (TC08, TC11).
Performance & Load: Large dataset response (TC10) and concurrent requests (TC15) test performance characteristics and load behavior.
Security: Basic security input validation / injection protection covered (TC12).
gaps: Pagination: No tests exercise pagination (limit/offset/page size), link/header-based pagination, or partial responses for very large datasets — only a monolithic 10,000-item test exists.
Caching Behavior: No scenarios validate caching-related headers or conditional requests (ETag, If-None-Match, Cache-Control, Last-Modified) or 304 Not Modified behavior.
Rate Limiting / Throttling: No tests assert rate limit enforcement (429 responses) or Retry-After behavior under high request rates.

Authorization granularity: No tests for authorization failures beyond authentication (e.g., valid token but insufficient privileges → 403), tenant-isolation enforcement beyond accountId scoping assertions.
Pagination performance/streaming: No tests for streaming/partial payloads or memory impact other than single large payload timing.
Content Negotiation / Accept header: No tests for varying Accept headers or responses when client requests non-JSON formats.
Response Ordering / Uniqueness / Deduplication: No tests assert ordering guarantees, stable sort, or duplicate handling in the returned date list (if required by API).
Header validation: No tests asserting other response headers (e.g., Content-Length, Cache-Control, custom headers) or presence/absence of sensitive headers on errors.
recommendations: Add pagination tests: verify limit, offset/page, page size params (if supported), header or link-based pagination, boundary conditions (page 0, page beyond last) and combine with large datasets to ensure correctness and performance.
Add caching/conditional request tests: assert ETag and/or Last-Modified headers, verify If-None-Match / If-Modified-Since behavior producing 304 Not Modified, and validate Cache-Control semantics.
Add rate-limiting tests: simulate high-frequency requests to assert 429 responses and Retry-After header behavior; include both authenticated and unauthenticated flows.
Add authorization/granularity tests: cover 403 forbidden scenarios where an authenticated token lacks required scope/role, and verify tenant isolation beyond simple accountId filtering.
Add content-negotiation tests: send Accept headers other than application/json and assert proper behavior (406 or correct content-type), and validate Content-Type correctness in all error paths.
Add tests for response ordering and uniqueness if the API contract requires a specific sort order or de-duplication of effective dates.
Add header and security hardening checks: ensure error responses do not leak sensitive internals in headers/bodies and validate presence/absence of safe headers (Content-Length, security headers).

Convert large-single-response tests to include pagination/streaming validation or verify server behavior under memory pressure; add monitoring of resource utilization and SLA thresholds beyond single timing assertion.
